data.content:
## Migration Analysis

Your code has **three** Thread.Abort patterns that need migration:

| Pattern | Location | Replacement |
|---------|----------|-------------|
| **Cancellable work loop** | `while (_running)` | `CancellationToken` |
| **ThreadAbortException as control flow** | `catch` block with `RollbackCurrentTransaction()` | `catch (OperationCanceledException)` |
| **Thread.ResetAbort to continue** | `ResetAbort()` to keep loop alive | `token.IsCancellationRequested` check |

## Why This Breaks on .NET 8

`Thread.Abort()` throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` — it simply doesn't work. `ThreadAbortException` is never thrown, so your cleanup code (`RollbackCurrentTransaction`) **silently stops running**. `Thread.ResetAbort()` also throws. Your `Stop()` method will crash.

## Migrated Code

```csharp
public class BackgroundProcessor : IDisposable
{
    private Thread? _workerThread;
    private CancellationTokenSource? _cts;

    public void Start()
    {
        _cts = new CancellationTokenSource();
        var token = _cts.Token;
        _workerThread = new Thread(() => ProcessLoop(token));
        _workerThread.IsBackground = true;
        _workerThread.Start();
    }

    private void ProcessLoop(CancellationToken token)
    {
        while (!token.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            try
            {
                var item = GetNextItem(token); // pass token so blocking can be interrupted
                ProcessItem(item, token);
            }
            catch (OperationCanceledException) when (token.IsCancellationRequested)
            {
                // Equivalent to the old ThreadAbortException catch block.
                // Clean up partial work, then let the loop exit naturally.
                RollbackCurrentTransaction();
            }
            finally
            {
                FlushBuffers();
            }
        }
    }

    public void Stop()
    {
        if (_cts is null || _workerThread is null)
            return;

        _cts.Cancel(); // signal cooperative cancellation

        // Give the thread time to finish gracefully
        if (!_workerThread.Join(TimeSpan.FromSeconds(2)))
        {
            // Thread didn't stop in time — log a warning.
            // There is NO equivalent to Thread.Abort() in .NET 8.
            // If GetNextItem blocks without checking the token, it will hang.
        }
    }

    public void Dispose()
    {
        Stop();
        _cts?.Dispose();
    }
}
```

## Key Changes Explained

1. **`CancellationTokenSource` replaces `Thread.Abort()`** — `_cts.Cancel()` signals all holders of the token cooperatively.

2. **`catch (OperationCanceledException)` replaces `catch (ThreadAbortException)`** — your `RollbackCurrentTransaction()` cleanup is preserved. The `when` filter ensures you only catch *your* cancellation.

3. **`Thread.ResetAbort()` is deleted** — no equivalent needed. The loop naturally checks `token.IsCancellationRequested` at the top and exits cleanly.

4. **`Thread.Sleep(2000)` → `_workerThread.Join(2s)`** — actually waits for the thread instead of sleeping and hoping.

5. **`IDisposable` added** — `CancellationTokenSource` leaks timers/callbacks if not disposed.

## Critical Pitfall: The Blocking `GetNextItem()`

Your comment says `GetNextItem()` "may block." **This is the hardest part.** Cooperative cancellation only works if the blocked code checks the token. You must update `GetNextItem` to accept and respect the token:

```csharp
// If it uses a BlockingCollection<T>:
private Item GetNextItem(CancellationToken token)
{
    return _queue.Take(token); // throws OperationCanceledException on cancel
}

// If it uses ManualResetEvent / WaitHandle:
private Item GetNextItem(CancellationToken token)
{
    WaitHandle.WaitAny(new[] { _dataReady, token.WaitHandle });
    token.ThrowIfCancellationRequested();
    return DequeueItem();
}

// If it uses Thread.Sleep for polling:
private Item GetNextItem(CancellationToken token)
{
    while (!HasData())
    {
        token.WaitHandle.WaitOne(500); // replaces Thread.Sleep(500)
        token.ThrowIfCancellationRequested();
    }
    return DequeueItem();
}
```

**If `GetNextItem` calls unmodifiable code** (third-party library, native I/O) that truly cannot accept a token, move it to a child `Process` and use `Process.Kill()` — that's the only safe force-termination left in .NET 8.

## Common Pitfalls Summary

| Pitfall | Why it matters |
|---------|---------------|
| Not passing token to `GetNextItem` | Thread hangs forever on `Stop()` — cancellation never reaches the blocking call |
| Forgetting to dispose `CancellationTokenSource` | Leaks internal timers and registered callbacks |
| Catching `OperationCanceledException` and swallowing it | Let it propagate except at the top-level loop; here we catch intentionally because we need `RollbackCurrentTransaction()` |
| Assuming cancellation is instant | It only fires at the next `ThrowIfCancellationRequested()` or token-aware wait — add checkpoints in `ProcessItem` if it's long-running |
